05971nam a22010215i 9783110596625DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019951898  a97831105966257 a10.1515/97831105966252doi  a(DE-B1597)494217  a(OCoLC)1135758388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP99.3b.G73 2020 4aP99.3b.G73 2020 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a401.412231 aGramigna, Remo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAugustine's Theory of Signs, Signification, and Lying /cRemo Gramigna. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XVI, 230 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Reason : Theory in the Study of Religion ,x0080-0848 ;v6000tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tList of figures/List of tables -- tIntroduction -- t1. Words as signs in the De Dialectica -- t2. On the conditions and possibilities of knowing: philosophy of semiosis in Augustine’s De magistro -- t3. Of ‘things’ and ‘signs’ in Augustine’s De Doctrina christiana -- t4. Mala fide communication: deception, misleading, and lying -- t5. Image, likeness, and falsity: from Soliloquia to De Trinitate -- tConclusions -- tBibliography -- tList of persons0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe aim of this study is to present, as far as possible, a general description of the theory of the sign and signification in Augustine of Hippo (354-430 AD), with a view to its evaluation and implications for the study of semiotics. Accurate studies for subject, discipline, and significance have not yet given an organic and systematic vision of Augustine’s theory of the sign. The underlying aspiration is that such an endeavour will prove to be beneficial to the scholars of Augustine’s thought as well as to those with a keen interest in the history of semiotics. The study uses Augustine’s own accounts to investigate and interpret the philosophical problem of the sign. The focus lies on the first decade of Augustine’s literary production. The De dialectica, is taken as the terminus ad quo of the study, and the De doctrina christiana is the terminus ad quem. The selected texts show an explicit engagement with poignant discussion on the nature and structure of the sign, the variety of signs and their uses. Although Augustine’s intention never was to establish a theory of meaning as an independent field of study, he largely employed a theory of signs. Thus, Augustine’s approach to signs is intrinsically meaningful.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aSemantics (Philosophy) 0aSemantics (Philosophy). 0aSemiotics. 0aSigns and symbols. 0aTruthfulness and falsehoodxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aAugustinus von Hippo. 4aLüge. 4aSemiotik. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAugustine of Hippo.  atheory of signs.  athe lie.  a semiotics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package